                                                "hideFigureFootnote": false,
                                                "markdown": "# POLICY BRIEF: Antenatal Care 4th Visit (ANC4) Coverage Gap\n\n## CONTEXT & PROBLEM STATEMENT\n\nAnalysis of ANC4 coverage data (2017-2025) reveals a **critical gap between health management information system (HMIS) reporting and actual service coverage**. While survey-based estimates indicate 82% coverage (2024), routine HMIS data captures only 65% coverage\u2014a **17 percentage point discrepancy**. This represents approximately **1 in 5 pregnant women** completing four antenatal visits but remaining invisible in routine health systems.\n\n### Key Findings:\n\n**Coverage Disparity Crisis:**\n- Survey estimates: 63% (2017) \u2192 82% (2024) [+19% improvement]\n- HMIS data: 0% (2017-2022) \u2192 65% (2025) [persistent underreporting]\n- **Gap magnitude: 17 percentage points** (2024-2025)\n\n**Data Quality Concerns:**\n- Zero reporting for 5 consecutive years (2017-2022) indicates systemic data collection failures\n- Late data capture initiation (2023) suggests recent system implementation\n- Stagnant HMIS growth (65% ceiling) despite survey evidence of higher coverage\n\n## POLICY RECOMMENDATIONS\n\n### 1. **IMMEDIATE: Data System Strengthening**\n- Conduct urgent HMIS audit to identify reporting bottlenecks\n- Implement mandatory ANC4 visit documentation protocols at all facilities\n- Deploy mobile health (mHealth) tools for real-time data capture\n\n### 2. **SHORT-TERM: Bridge the Reporting Gap**\n- Train 100% of frontline health workers on ANC4 data recording standards\n- Establish monthly data quality verification meetings at district level\n- Integrate community health worker records into national HMIS\n\n### 3. **LONG-TERM: System Integration**\n- Link patient identifiers across facilities to prevent double-counting\n- Develop interoperable digital health platforms\n- Institutionalize annual data validation surveys\n\n**Expected Impact:** Closing this 17% gap would improve resource allocation accuracy, enable evidence-based planning, and ensure no pregnant woman is lost to follow-up."
